article.headline: Seton Hall 79, Rhode Island 67
article.story: EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- Rhode Island head coach Jim Baron can be added to the litany of those currently singing the praises of Seton Hall senior point guard Andre Barrett. "Andre Barrett is as good as any point guard in the nation," Baron said after Barrett scored 23 points and added 12 assists in a 79-67 Seton Hall victory over Rhode Island Thursday night. "He just makes it go," Baron said. "He makes his share of shots, but he also makes everyone else on the floor so much better. He's so smart and makes the right plays." Barrett, who has averaged nearly 21 points and eight assists per game over the last nine contests, led Seton Hall (9-2) to its sixth straight victory and its seventh in eight games. It also enabled the Pirates to increase their current home winning streak to 13 games, the longest since 1995 and the second longest since the Pirates started calling the Continental Airlines Arena home in the 1985-86 season. While Baron was impressed with Barrett's performance, Seton Hall coach Louis Orr considered it just another typical outing from Barrett. "I've been watching him play for three years and I probably take some of the things Andre does for granted," Orr said. "He's really developing into the total package and I'm happy for him. Great players do great things and Andre Barrett is a great player. He carried us in the first half and did what he had to do for us to win." Barrett scored 15 of his points in the first half, enabling Seton Hall to take a 38-34 halftime lead. He then engineered two second-half runs that carried the team to the win. "When I step on the floor, I feel like I'm the best player," Barrett said. "It's not a matter of cockiness, but it's just the way I feel. I think we're all playing with a lot of confidence right now and that's been the key." Barrett was one of four Pirates to register double figures. John Allen contributed 21 points, including several key shots in the second half, after Rhode Island (10-3) sliced a 15-point lead down to four. Allen nailed a corner jumper that pushed the lead to 66-60, then canned a long 3-pointer that increased the lead back to 69-60 with 4:17 left. "I was open and I could feel it," Allen said. "I took those shots with confidence and it swung the momentum back our way. I think we all have a lot of confidence out there and it shows. It shows that we're a more mature team." Seton Hall is also enjoying its best start since the 2000-01 season, when they were 10-2 under former coach Tommy Amaker. "I don't think we have the same talent as we did that year," said Barrett, alluding to the Seton Hall team that also featured current NBA players Eddie Griffin and Samuel Dalembert. "But we play together as a team more and have the right components to keep it going." The Pirates also received 17 points from Andre Sweet and 10 from J.R. Morris coming off the bench. Dawan Robinson scored 19 points and Scott Hazelton added 13 for Rhode Island. The win also avenged Seton Hall's 61-60 loss to Rhode Island in the opening round of the National Invitation Tournament last March.
